definition.value: An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of any ditrans,polycis-polyprenyl diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of any peptidylamidoglycolate; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide cation obtained by protonation of the amino terminus of any peptidylamide; major species at pH 7.3.

A methyl-branched lipid having at least one methyl group  branched at C(omega-1) and either a single or a double bond between C(omega-1)  and C(omega-2). The class includes both (omega-1)-methyl-branched fatty acids and derivatives.

A methyl-branched lipid having an OH group at position Comega, at least one methyl group  branched at C(omega-1) and either a single or a double bond between C(omega-1)  and C(omega-2). The class includes both (omega-1)-methyl-branched fatty alcohols and derivatives.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of lithocholic acid 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid functions; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid acid anion that has a carboxylate group located at the 4alpha-position together with a hydroxy substituent located at the 3beta-position. Major microspecies at pH 7.4.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxyestrone 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxyestrone 2-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 4-hydroxyestrone 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of estrone 4-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 2-methoxyestrone 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A 17-oxo steroid that is estrone in which the hydrogen at position 4 has been replaced by a methoxy group.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 4-methoxyestrone 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 2-methoxy-17beta-estradiol 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A 17beta-hydroxy steroid that is 17beta-estradiol in which the hydrogen at position 4 has been replaced by a methoxy group.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 4-methoxy-17beta-estradiol 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A 7-methyl guanosine (m7G) linked via an inverted 5'-5' triphosphate bridge to an initiating 2'-O-methyl-purine-ribonucleotide-ribonucleotide; major species at pH 7.3
A 7-methyl guanosine (m7G) linked via an inverted 5'-5' triphosphate bridge to an initiating 2'-O-methyl-purine-ribonucleotide-2'-O-methyl-ribonucleotide; major species at pH 7.3
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of isowyosine 5'-monophosphate residue; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-hydroxy steroid that is 2-hydroxyestrone in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has been converted to the corresponding methyl ether.

A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of 5alpha-androstane-3beta,17beta-diol 17-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 5alpha-dihydrotestosterone sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of (3beta,5alpha,17beta)-3-hydroxyandrostan-17-yl sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group; major species at pH 7.3.
An EC 4.4.1.* (C-S lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylate synthase (EC 4.4.1.14).
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of S-prenyl-L-cysteine; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyhexacosanoic acid.
An L-glutamic acid derivative obtained by replacement of one of the amino hydrogens of L-glutamic acid has been replaced by a (2S)-2-amino-2-carboxyethyl group.
An N-(polyunsaturated fatty acyl)ethanolamine obtained by formal epoxidation across the 5,6-double bond of anandamide.
An N-(polyunsaturated fatty acyl)ethanolamine obtained by formal epoxidation across the 8,9-double bond of anandamide.
An N-(polyunsaturated fatty acyl)ethanolamine obtained by formal epoxidation across the 11,12-double bond of anandamide.
An N-(polyunsaturated fatty acyl)ethanolamine obtained by formal epoxidation across the 14,15-double bond of anandamide.
An N-(polyunsaturated fatty acyl)ethanolamine that is anandamide in which one of the methyl hydrogens at position 20 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A tricarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups and protonation of the amino group of staphyloferrin B; major species at pH 7.3.
A glutathione conjugate in which the thiol hydrogen of glutathione has been replaced by a 2,5-dihydroxyphenyl group.
An  aromatic ether that is the derivative of 2-phenylethylamine with methoxy substituents at the 3- and 4-positions. It is an alkaloid isolated from the Cactaceae family.
A fatty acid ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of oleic acid with the hydroxy group of 9-hydroxyoctadecanoic acid.
A class of sulfur-containing amino acids consisting of homologues of methionine where there is a minimum of four methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
An L-polyhomomethionine in which there are four methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
An L-polyhomomethionine in which there are five methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the OH group of C-terminal Xaa-Gly residue
An alkylamino group derived from any alpha-amino-acid amide.
An L-polyhomomethionine in which there are six methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
An organic anionic group obtained by deprotonation of the OH group of C-terminal Xaa-hydroxyglycino residue.
An L-polyhomomethionine in which there are seven methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
An L-polyhomomethionine in which there are eight methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
A class of N-hydroxy-alpha-amino-acids consisting of homologues of N-hydroxymethionine where there is a minimum of four methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.
A class of N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino-acids consisting of homologues of N,N-dihydroxymethionine where there is a minimum of four methylene groups between the alpha-carbon and sulfur atoms.

A 1-(alk-1Z-enyl)-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(N-acyl)ethanolamine(1-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of 1-O-(1Z-octadecenyl)-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(N-hexadecanoyl)ethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.

A 1-(alk-1Z-enyl)-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(N-acyl)ethanolamine(1-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of 1-(1Z-octadecenyl)-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(N-oleoyl)ethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
